&lt;p/&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There seems to be no easy way at this moment to apply this. Of course you could use the headers parameter in the @RequestMapping, but that doesn&apos;t work when a request is done without the accept header using an extension in the url instead (e.g. list.xml). When using an url extension as in the above example it doesn&apos;t work when only the accept header is set.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;JAX-RS has a @Produces and @Consumes annotation which does the job perfectly. Wouldn&apos;t we need something similar in Spring?&lt;/p&gt;


